In the last part of the passage the words mentem intentam infixamque nostram intellegentiam capere are evidently to be understood not of the simple contemplation or perception by the mens, but rather of the process of reasoning which follows, examines and searches for the true purport of our perceptions. Perception alone is only receptive and can naturally give only the species deornm, as Cotta (§ 107) rightly remarks; but a percep- tion that is only receptive and passive is not enough for the human mind 3 it is thereby roused to an individual activity. This is again of two kinds ι first, so to speak‚ a cursory one, and the ideas which come from it spon· taneously are very properly called προλήψεις, notiones anticipator, ante· ceptae informationes (ξ 43). If they are sometimes called intellegentiae, this is hardly done without an epithet to denote their nature, such as in· elautae, adumbratae, obscurae, Cic. De Leg. 1, 9, 25 ; 10, 303 22, 59 (comp. on De Offic. This is denoted by the Greek insititiam, ἐπιβολὴ (Schneider ad Epicur. Physic, p. 65), and Cicero expresses it by animus se iniciens et intendem, or, asin our passage, niens intenta infixaque.

Now if the intellegentia thus gained is spoken of as one qnae sit et hato natura et aeterna it is plainly nonsense; and this is generally ac· knowledged. The emendation I (Prof. Sch.) proposed in my Opusc. Acad. IV, 347 Ι called paullo obscurior,· but it is not so obscure that it might not be understood with a little thought. Bake’s quam sit ea beata natura et aeterna (Mnemosyn. 11, p. 415) may be easier so far as the Mss. are concerned; but one of the defenders of this reading has not over- looked the fact that qnam cannot possibly be taken of the measure or degree of happiness and immortality of the gods. He has recourse there· fore to the assumption that the difficulty of the passage results from a rather stupid misunderstanding on the part of Cicero. He thinks Cicero found in the Greek original that he was translating ὥς, which there had the force of ὅτι corresponding to “ that'' introducing a sentence 3 and that he erroneously took this for the adverb equivalent to qnantum or quantopere. lfCrcero had found ὡς in the original, he would have translated it by nt, as he did in the phrase of Protagoras in c. 23, 63.
